This patch effectively includes all of the changes from the linked patch.  You should use that patch as a base instead of directly copying over the code.
The generated file is not actually being used by the BMCWeb executable so I don't think it's getting pulled in.
Overall looks like a good start.  Just need to get the corner cases handled
Use constexpr instead
This is incorrect.  /redfish does not have the type ServiceRoot.
Can we drop these names in the generated code, and use either * or {}?  The actual name here doesn't matter to this data structure.
Looks incorrect.  Actions I think have their own type?
This isn't right.  /redfish/v1/AccountService/ActiveDirectory isn't a valid URI, given that ActiveDirectory is a property, not a NavigationResource.

What if the inputs are "/redfish/v1/" and "/redfish/v1"?  Those should count as a match, but I don't think this function accounts for trailing "/".

You might also have false positives with something like "/redfish/v1/Chassis" and "/redfish/v1/Chassis/{ChassisId}".  I think even "/redfish" and "/redfish/<anything else>" will return as a match.

Add some test cases for this function.

Is the passed URI always going to be the Redfish handler routes which include a wildcard or will they be the URI supplied by an actual request?  If it's the former then it'd be easier to modify the array entries to make the wildcards match.
You should be able to use std::binary_search so that you aren't iterating over every array entry in order.
By redfish definitions, is this a Registry?  It doesn't seem like it would be.
Can we just write the below in a normal c++ file?  I don't see anything generated in the below, and it looks self contained.

I think you should avoid having your script generate actual C++ functions.  For one thing it's going to be a headache if they need to be modified for any reason.  Create a separate file for these functions and let them pull from the generated array of URIs.

Renaming this makes sense, but the new name hides that it's still generating top collections.  The file itself is still called "generate_schema_collections.py".  Try to combine those in some way to indicate that the function is generating both registries and top level collections.
Can you add another test to make sure it's able to tell when a passed URI is not in the registry?

I've rebased the patches to denote the appropriate history, and I've stacked a patch at the end to start fixing some of the issues.

Carson/Edward, please review the fixes, and I'm happy to either merge the series as it stands, or integrate my fixes into one of the other patchsets, but I think it's good enough to go on master.
